<subSubSection id="C33D9BB5FFDEFF81FF7AE0D2FC46F9D7" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B98C83EFFDEFF81FF7AE0D2FE61FA87" blockId="30.[151,1437,266,1332]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFDEFF81FF7AE0D2FEB0FABF" bold="true" box="[198,331,1266,1292]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Etymology</emphasis>
. This species is named for Oliver Flint, Jr., a noted neuropterist and trichopterist and the collector of the 
<typeStatus id="549C769CFFDEFF81FE97E13AFE6DFA87" box="[299,406,1306,1332]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98C83EFFDEFF81FD2EE1A7FC5AFA12" blockId="30.[658,929,1415,1441]" box="[658,929,1415,1441]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFDEFF81FD2EE1A7FC5AFA12" bold="true" box="[658,929,1415,1441]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
C. The 
<taxonomicName id="4C27B3BDFFDEFF81FD51E1A7FCB5FA12" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName=": Brown" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[749,846,1415,1441]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plenana">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFDEFF81FD51E1A7FCB5FA12" bold="true" box="[749,846,1415,1441]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">plenana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98C83EFFDEFF81FF2BE1F2FC46F9D7" blockId="30.[151,1436,1490,1636]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
The divergent male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="4C27B3BDFFDEFF81FDADE1F3FD6DFA5F" authorityName="Brown" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName=": Brown" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[529,662,1491,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Megalota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plenana">
<emphasis id="B953142CFFDEFF81FDADE1F3FD6DFA5F" box="[529,662,1491,1516]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">M. plenana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhibit its confident placement in either of the proposed informal species groups. The basal process of the valva is extraordinarily long, longer than the valva, with an unusual pointed process apically; the uncus is strongly flattened; and the valva is short and narrow. Discovery of the female likely will help resolve the taxonomic position of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
